{"type":"message","id":"23492503","parentId":"183e20dd","timestamp":"2026-06-11T09:37:20.399Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK, so the first bytes are `56314d4d5758` which is `\"V1MMWX\"` in ASCII. This looks like a PC WeChat wxapkg file. The magic is `V1MMWX` which is the typical PC WeChat Mini Program package format.\n\nFor PC WeChat wxapkg files (as opposed to mobile), the format is different:\n- Magic bytes: `V1MMWX` (or `V1MMWX` has some variants)\n- The actual content is XOR encrypted and/or gzipped\n\nLet me look up the exact format. The `wxappUnpacker` tool and other tools can handle this.\n\nLet me try a different approach - install a tool that can handle this. Or write my own unpacker based on known format.\n\nThe known format for PC WeChat wxapkg:\n- `V1MMWX` is the magic header (6 bytes)\n- Then there's some header info\n- The data is XOR-encrypted using a key derived from the first bytes\n\nActually, let me check more of the file to understand the structure.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_uJz71U9kLdgB2JY6VehF9096","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"node -e \"\nconst fs=require('fs');\nconst b=fs.readFileSync('C:\\\\Users\\\\yyzypublic\\\\Downloads\\\\__APP__.wxapkg');\nconsole.log('Magic:', b.slice(0,6).toString());\n// Check more headers\nlet offset = 6;\nconsole.log('After magic (len 10):', b.slice(6,16).toString('hex'));\n// Check data at various offsets for zlib magic\nfor(let o=0;o<200;o+=1){\n  if(b[o]===0x78 && (b[o+1]===0x01 || b[o+1]===0x5e || b[o+1]===0x9c || b[o+1]===0xda)){\n    console.log('zlib header found at offset:', o, 'hex:', b.slice(o, o+4).toString('hex'));\n  }\n}\n// Check for 'config' or 'app' strings\nconst str = b.slice(0, 500).toString('utf8');\nconsole.log('First 500 bytes as string:', str.replace(/[\\x00-\\x1f\\x80-\\xff]/g, '.').substring(0, 200));\n\"","timeout":10}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-