{"type":"message","id":"211b9ae0","parentId":"ba5df0f1","timestamp":"2026-06-11T09:37:50.052Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK, so the file starts with `V1MMWX` (6 bytes) followed by what seems to be XOR-encrypted data. The data doesn't look like plaintext - it's probably XOR encrypted.\n\nFor PC WeChat wxapkg, the common decryption method involves:\n1. XOR with the first 6 bytes (magic \"V1MMWX\")\n2. But that doesn't yield clean results here\n\nLet me try a more well-known approach. Many PC wxapkg tools use a specific decryption algorithm. Let me install one of the well-known tools or implement the decryption.\n\nActually, let me try a more comprehensive approach. The PC WeChat wxapkg decryption typically works like this:\n\nFrom the source: https://github.com/poer/wxappUnpacker\n\nThe newer format uses:\n- Magic: `V1MMWX` (or `V1`) \n- XOR encryption with a key derived from the magic or file\n\nLet me try another approach - download and use a known working tool. But since the network is restricted, let me try to write a decryption script.\n\nActually, let me look at this more carefully. The PC WeChat mini program format for newer versions:\n\n1. Magic: \"V1MMWX\" (6 bytes)\n2. XOR key: \"V1MMWX\" repeated, XOR with the first few bytes?\n\nActually, I should look for the wechat mini program format spec more carefully.\n\nLet me try a different approach - look for the well-known decryption method used by tools like `wxappUnpacker`.\n\nThe standard method for PC wxapkg (版本2格式):\n- Read first 3 bytes as header: \"V1M\" or \"V2M\"\n- There's a specific XOR process\n\nLet me try to look for tooling or write a proper decryption.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_BdUfvmC9tPITgmOoWNkb4072","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"const fs = require('fs');\nconst zlib = require('zlib');\n\nconst filePath = 'C:\\\\Users\\\\yyzypublic\\\\Downloads\\\\__APP__.wxapkg';\nconst b = fs.readFileSync(filePath);\n\nconsole.log('=== PC WeChat wxapkg Decrypt Attempt ===');\nconsole.log('File size:', b.length);\n\n// The magic for PC wxapkg is 'V1MMWX' (6 bytes)\nconst magic = b.slice(0, 6);\nconsole.log('Magic:', magic.toString());\n\n// Common approaches for PC wxapkg decryption:\n\n// Approach 1: XOR all data after magic with the magic key\nfunction tryDecrypt(buf, key) {\n  const out = Buffer.alloc(buf.length);\n  for (let i = 0; i < buf.length; i++) {\n    out[i] = buf[i] ^ key[i % key.length];\n  }\n  return out;\n}\n\n// Approach 2: PC wxapkg sometimes uses XOR with shifted keys\n// The encrypted data starts at offset 6\nconst encrypted = b.slice(6);\n\n// Try different XOR keys\nconst keys = [\n  'V1MMWX',\n  'MMWX',\n  'V1M',\n  'WeChat',\n  'wxapkg',\n  Buffer.from([0x56, 0x31, 0x4d, 0x4d, 0x57, 0x58]) // V1MMWX\n];\n\nfor (const key of keys) {\n  const dec = tryDecrypt(encrypted, Buffer.isBuffer(key) ? key : Buffer.from(key));\n  // Look for zlib magic 0x789c or 0x78da\n  for (let o = 0; o < Math.min(1000, dec.length - 2); o++) {\n    if ((dec[o] === 0x78 && (dec[o+1] === 0x9c || dec[o+1] === 0xda))) {\n      console.log(`\\nFound zlib at offset ${o} with key \"${Buffer.isBuffer(key) ? key.toString() : key}\"`);\n      try {\n        const decompressed = zlib.inflateSync(dec.slice(o));\n        const text = decompressed.toString('utf8').substring(0, 500);\n        console.log('Decompressed data preview:', text);\n      } catch(e) {\n        console.log('But inflate failed:', e.message);\n      }\n    }\n  }\n}\n\n// Approach 3: Sometimes it's NOT XOR - it could be AES or just plain zlib\n// Check if there's a zlib stream somewhere in the encrypted file\nconsole.log('\\nChecking for raw zlib in original data...');\nfor (let o = 0; o < Math.min(2000, b.length - 2); o++) {\n  if ((b[o] === 0x78 && (b[o+1] === 0x9c || b[o+1] === 0xda))) {\n    console.log(`Raw zlib at offset ${o}`);\n    try {\n      const decompressed = zlib.inflateSync(b.slice(o));\n      const text = decompressed.toString('utf8').substring(0, 200);\n      if (text.includes('{') || text.includes('app')) {\n        console.log('Decompressed:', text);\n      }\n    } catch(e) {}\n  }\n}\n\n// Approach 4: Some PC wxapkg use a simpler encryption\n// The key idea: the first 1024 bytes are XOR encrypted with a rolling key\n// Try reading the file directly as structured data\n// Look for the \"header\" structure\nconsole.log('\\n=== Trying structured read ===');\n// Some PC wxapkg have a simple structure:\n// [magic][4-byte filecount][file records...][data...]\n// Try reading as LE or BE integers\nconst readU32LE = (buf, off) => buf.readUInt32LE(off);\nconst readU32BE = (buf, off) => buf.readUInt32BE(off);\n\n// The XOR key might be derived from the file path\n// Path: __APP__.wxapkg\n// Try different keys derived from the filename\nconst fileKeys = [\n  '__APP__',\n  '__APP__.wxapkg',\n  'APP',\n  'app',\n  'WeChat',\n  'wx',\n  'wxapp'\n];\nfor (const key of fileKeys) {\n  const dec = tryDecrypt(b, Buffer.from(key));\n  for (let o = 0; o < Math.min(1000, dec.length - 2); o++) {\n    if ((dec[o] === 0x78 && (dec[o+1] === 0x9c || dec[o+1] === 0xda))) {\n      console.log(`\\nFound zlib after decrypt with key \"${key}\" at offset ${o}`);\n      try {\n        const decompressed = zlib.inflateSync(dec.slice(o));\n        const text = decompressed.toString('utf8').substring(0, 300);\n        console.log('Decompressed:', text);\n      } catch(e) {}\n    }\n  }\n}\n","path":"C:\\Users\\yyzypublic\\.openclaw\\workspace\\decrypt_wxapkg.js"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":240,"output":1588,"cacheRead":19328,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":21156,"cost":{"input":0.000033600000000000004,"output":0.00044464000000000005,"cacheRead":0.000541184,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0010194240000000001}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1781170654033,"responseId":"93f6185c-9ec5-45ec-ae74-bf613640a798"}}
