{"type":"message","id":"0cc50758","parentId":"b0cd53e1","timestamp":"2026-06-11T09:38:04.363Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have the key info. The encryption uses:\n\n1. PBKDF2 to generate an AES key\n2. Pass: WeChat Mini Program ID (appid)\n3. Salt: \"saltiest\"\n4. Iterations: 1000\n5. Generates 32-byte key (AES-256)\n6. IV: 16 bytes of a specific value (from the tool, it's \"the iv: 16 bytes ...\")\n7. Encrypts first 1023 bytes with AES\n\nAlso, the file at offset 6 contains the encrypted header info.\n\nThe tool `pc_wxapkg_decrypt` by oslijw on Gitee might work, but it requires the appid (wxid).\n\nBut wait - `zqw.wxapkg` in the workspace - maybe I can find the appid. Let me check the file name. The user has `__APP__.wxapkg` in Downloads. But there's also `zqw.wxapkg` in workspace. Let me check.\n\nAlso, from the CSDN article and Gitee repo, the decryption needs the WeChat Mini Program's AppID. But there's an important detail - for the PC version, the `__APP__.wxapkg` file's metadata contains the appid in an unencrypted form somewhere, or we need to find it.\n\nLet me try a simpler approach first. The CSDN article mentions a 3-step approach. Let me fetch that article.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_sWf7wUFD7xcfSQD98X1d9439","name":"web_fetch","arguments":{"url":"https://blog.csdn.net/gitblog_01075/article/details/156262023","maxChars":5000}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_01_gBczBIgCqnf8NyHtLqZS2756","name":"web_fetch","arguments":{"url":"https://gitee.com/oslijw/pc_wxapkg_decrypt","maxChars":5000}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":1579,"output":456,"cacheRead":21632,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":23667,"cost":{"input":0.00022106000000000003,"output":0.00012768,"cacheRead":0.000605696,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.000954436}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1781170678379,"responseId":"36c8cd43-80ca-4bac-b3e9-2c75bc